Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
Inflation was higher than expected in November in the 13 euro-zone countries - an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded after the 2.6 per cent recorded in October, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
According to Bloomberg, official forecasts were only 3 percent.
In contrast to the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the Leitzsins. In its opinion, the reduction in interest rates would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment in the wake of an inflation spiral.
The ECB strives to keep inflation below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a dilemma: inflation has to be "agreed" in order to avoid any need for action later on.
At 3.3 percent, inflation in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone was driven by the rise in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and soybean prices also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in prices for edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is expected to decline to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 per cent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to lower interest rates twice.
Gallup sets up government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably until the beginning of December. First since 2002, the party has had the largest base camp, while the support for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
Among party-faithful voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two thirds (71 percent) are opposed to one fifth (20 percent) approval of the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry threshold: they come to two percent in the total population.
The number of party voters in both camps has grown by one percent.
Compared to the last low point, the general economic sentiment has deteriorated further - never before has the proportion of those who consider the country's economic situation to be "very bad" been so high (41 percent), while a further 46 percent consider it to be "quite bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, the families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate further; only one tenth is expected to improve.
A Gallup survey conducted in December showed that 71% of respondents - a historic high - rated the Prime Minister's work as "rather bad than right".
Thirteen percent of respondents have great trust or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the share of supporters for Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the party leader of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be controlled even without a change of government.
After last October's riots, 35% of the people who voted for the government and the head of government remained in office, this figure now stands at only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked for their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would "participate with certainty" and another 20% would "probably" cast their vote.
By way of comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would go "with certainty" to the polls, another 15% would consider their participation to be "probable". In view of these trends, the outcome of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fees, and 84% against the hospital daily allowance.
Imposed on the group of those who took part in the referendum "with certainty" the shares of the opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would be even 81, 84, and 89 per cent respectively.
