In many places disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were recorded in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overburdening of staff - all factors that are not conducive to the containment of infections, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
The traumatology department of János Hospital recently diagnosed a MRSA infection.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient has been isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with a MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient’s body.
Until 10 December of this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens from hospitals were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are dosed too much or used improperly, the well-responsive bacteria result in antibiotic-resistant bacteria that spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday sick house life.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA there are only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nurses wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients are examined for MRSA when they are admitted to hospital, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for the control of the formation or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients who have been admitted and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, sampling of microbiological samples is not so common.
Not least because there are no subsidies on the part of the state health insurance fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light if the patient already had a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology centre.
On the part of the European Union, there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological investigations are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug from developing, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatients or patients in primary care.
Saved for disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transferred from one patient to the other by nursing staff.
It is precisely for this reason that hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted through droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient in the domestic hospitals.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are narrowly lined up, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the less well-placed hospitals it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that almost favour the emergence of infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, such infections are far less common there, or can be prevented from spreading the pathogen where these protective measures are observed.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting a grip on MRSA infections causes enormous costs to health insurance companies, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
