Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe looks attentive to the Balkan state, which was rarely mentioned earlier.
What, where, and who still buys the cheapest market in the EU, but which is rapidly getting more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most sought-after place to buy real estate in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the Renner, but properties around Kavarna and Balcik are increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will attract investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favorable area of Russe has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - trade and office space offer highest returns.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive European golfers' paradises, and thus to attract tourists in addition to the summer and winter season also in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while the Black Sea and ski resorts are predominantly Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle buy either revitalized properties for 500,100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are important, but the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are also crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was ranked among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of businessmen who invest in order to increase medium to long-term value.
Real estate in the capital, however, is becoming more and more expensive, due to the ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are lowest in Bulgaria, but there has been an annual increase of 21 percent over the past five years.
The price increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries discuss the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol expires.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be prepared to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue of the conference is whether developed countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on support for developing countries.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, probably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (in line with 1990 levels), regardless of whether the "Agreement after 2012" was successful or not. In fact, the Union would be prepared to commit itself to a 30% reduction if other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, were also willing to fulfil their commitments as efficiently and responsibly as possible.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the goal of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its 15 member states at the time, had already committed itself to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The deployment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans laid down in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by a renewed international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee of the UN, which has been awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in its recent report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and increase the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, leading to extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British army advertises on YouTube
British Army units have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube: Special Forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos about operations against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The images shot with miniature cameras attached to helmets are controlled at the air base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message unavoidable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under defenceheadquarters in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Foreign Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the Iraq-based International Peacekeeping Forces (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Luftwaffe published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and, as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population of the actual objectives of foreign operations.
According to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie of the BBC, propaganda published in this way is almost free of charge, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
American advertising with game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to carefully processed, censored recordings, also make it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are at most discussed, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, by the way, numerous videos filmed in action have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genuine" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "Americas Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-scattered simulation.
