More and more forces mobilized for giant-strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Trade Union Federation will form their coordinating committee on Friday for an indefinite strike beginning on Monday.
On Saturday a protest general assembly will be held, on Monday - on the day of the referendum on the Health Insurance Act - the stoppage of work will begin.
Strike-related, significant traffic obstructions are expected, as rail transport is almost completely stopped, and Budapest's public transport companies (BKV) are also on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of the strike on Monday will be announced by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee is also set up, which is responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
On Saturday, a protest general assembly will be held, and from Monday, all organizations that have joined the strike will cease work indefinitely unless agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike, which began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act, was not defined.
If the National Council does not adopt the Health Insurance Act, the unions immediately withdraw the call for strike.
If the law is passed, however, the strike committees meet to discuss the future course of action.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that the vote on the Health Insurance Act will only take place in the late evening hours, or even at midnight.
The strikes, which begin on Monday, will have to count on significant traffic obstructions: the railway workers lay down their work for an indefinite period of time, in the morning the majority of public transport and more than half of the Volán companies stand still.
At the same time, there will be motorway closures in many places in one direction.
