The Hungarian Medical Association is on an alternating strike at various times throughout the country, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SCEF, the forum for trade union cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraws the draft health insurance reform and presents a new concept for social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
Claim number three states that the eligible occupational groups will be given access to the early retirement scheme before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ belonging to the League of Trade Unions did not accept the offer submitted by the Ministry of Transport concerning the secondary lines and now calls for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
Among other things, the Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states that in the context of the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "enhancement of existing ethnic tensions between Gypsies and non-Gypsies in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such an argument, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition".
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, thanks not least to the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, "have seriously damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember that since autumn 2006 the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been on the upswing, so that since summer 2007 several organizations called "National Self-Defense Association" have been founded.
"These groups are in common that they each define themselves as a civil organization, while openly brag about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (catastrophe protection, national defence, protection of order), citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further: All this should be done according to the method that seeks to disguise various political aspirations as bourgeois initiatives, based on the political and party displeasure of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association thus serve not only to circumvent legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration at the court - it is also a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, some ultra-nationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region" - it said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central-Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was founded in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard stood the Roma mass riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
