Balázs Zságer started in Pécs, playing music himself in the band Yonderboi, before he - perhaps because an inn can't handle two pipers - started his own way.
The breakthrough with his project (Zagar) and his music, which fuses elements from jazz, electronic, and pop, was only achieved when one had approached him with the request to compose the soundtrack to a film (e.g.
"Szezon" by Ferenc Török).
The formation, which had initially appeared in smaller clubs, became known to the wider audience only when the magazine "wan2" ranked their first album from 2002 among the top 50 domestic albums and Zagar, together with Yonderboi, became the almost only trendsetter, also marketable in the West.
Undoubtedly, Zagar and his band were "trendy", but no one was interested in whether they liked to wear this brand.
The band reacted as it should: with a new, even better album.
The new album with the title "Cannot Walk Fly Instead" could open up new paths for them, but the title already expresses the desire for continuity with the Pécs years.
The term comes from the time when Balázs Zságer was still with another band.
The airy, flying allusion would also be fine, but apart from the ethereal character of the music, the pure guitar, the influences of rock'n'roll, according to the zeitgeist and the trends, are noticeable.
With these songs, singer György Ligeti, who lives in England and works with the band "The Puzzle", introduced himself at the premiere in Millenáris.
A song from the album has even made it to the radio hit - the recent pop music broadcaster Mr2 Petőfi has gradually caught the listener's attention with the number "Wings of Love", which was recorded with the participation of six domestic singers ("Underground Divas").
So everything's all right (?).
The hvg.hu asked Balázs Zságer.
hvg.hu: This new hit raises the question: To what extent is your music reserved for a certain layer?
Balázs Zságer: The term "shift music" does not mean much to me.
In my opinion, there are two boxes in pop music, not mainstream and underground, or alternative and pop, but commercial and honest.
Even the so-called alternative or underground music can be shallow and meaningless, but they can also only be produced for sale, which makes them commercial music.
A good pop number can also come from an honest motive.
The listener's willingness to record also works according to this principle, independent of languages and national borders.
hvg.hu: Do you see a difference in the openness of Hungarian and foreign audiences to your music?
B. Zs.: In foreign countries, especially to the west of us, pop music has a greater tradition.
Not only teenagers or Twens go to concerts, but also the older audience.
They follow the trends in pop music that are happening around them much more attentively because they also consider it to be part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What role does the audience play in your work?
Is it important who, where, how many listen to your music?
B. Zs.: Of course it is a good feeling to see that more and more come to our concerts.
But we never composed for the market.
We do not create music to serve a purpose, but for a reason.
The role of the audience is usually noticeable at the concerts, where there is already a mutual interaction, but these in turn exist only in the incomprehensible changes of the moment.
Still, I noticed that if you want to please everyone, you're no longer interesting.
hvg.hu: How far do you want to follow the example of Yonderboi?
He is on the road as a soloist and has built up his career in the West.
B. Zs.: We don’t really go his way, not to mention trying to interpret this into our music time and time again.
We see ourselves as more of a team player who trusts in the musical presence of the other and lets them unfold.
At first, of course, comparisons of our work with that of Yonderboi were inevitable, as several of us came out of his band and took a different path.
hvg.hu: In the charts of mr2 Petőfi, "Wings of Love" comes first.
Many have only heard the name Zagar in connection with this number.
Was the opening deliberately staged with a somewhat more popular style towards a wider audience?
B. Zs.: We had no plans to write a hit, which should then be considered a draw horse for the album.
This song is about more.
It was intended as the finale of the album, with which we wanted to dissolve the sound orgy and the somewhat more difficult themes.
hvg.hu: How did you choose the six singers?
Why them, what was the guiding principle?
B. Zs.: The basic idea was to make a gospel-like choir.
Then came the idea of putting together the choir of talented soloists from the local music scene.
This is how the six-member choir was created - that is, Sena, Edina Kutzora, Judie Jay, Bori Péterfy, Enikő Hodosi [Neo], Juci Németh - which we then baptized "Underground Divas".
hvg.hu: Did you want the song the same way, or did the girls do it?
B. Zs.: The number has been in the instrumental version for some time, but when the material for the album was finished, we thought that this number still "needs something".
The chord sequence has formally demanded a vocal voice.
I sang the melody the same night, later they learned the girls.
It all came in handy right away and frighteningly spontaneous.
I can remember, I was quite electrified at the time, but the "Divas" was already in need.
With my voice alone, the song would never have become so strong.
hvg.hu: Both on the record and at the concert you had the impression that the girls were in the background.
There is no solo part (apart from Judy Jay's short solo), they have no role of their own, sing together completely and are not louder than the music, so their singing is not only accompanied by the music.
They were also standing on the back of the stage.
Is it on purpose?
B.Zs.: The fact that they were in the back was because of purely technical problems.
However, we deliberately did not want to give them solo roles.
In the number it is also a matter of forgetting one's ego a little, forgetting who came from where and where we are going, we simply allow these particular wings, the wings of love, to lift us up.
I would like others to feel the euphoric state that we felt when the song came into being.
hvg.hu: Which was the most elaborate song?
B. Zs.: With the musical work actually none, there have been more difficult tasks when mixing.
For example, in "Dorian Gray's Dilemma", in which I play on a concert piano, or in "Rock'n'Roll Goes To The Girls", where the groove didn't want to work any longer, but gradually everything got together, like in a puzzle.
hvg.hu: What is your favorite number from the new album?
B. Zs.: This is constantly changing with the concerts and now that I have left the album "losen".
Currently it is "Prophet Is A Fool", "Escape From The Earth" and the number "Never The Same".
