For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented to a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been charged with insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced to 15 days in prison and subsequently expelled by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening.
The British woman was accused of having allowed six to seven-year-old students to give the name Mahomet to a teddy bear, even though any portrayal of the Islamic prophet is forbidden.
She deserved to be flogged.
After parents of students complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture several times, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at the Unity High School in Khartoum, was picked up at home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six to seven-year-old student to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed , reports headmaster Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
Certainly, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all also a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed .
The bear himself did not wear a shield with that name, but the problem is quite simply that the portrayal of the Islamic Prophet is regarded as an insult to Islam.
