Pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall in; his way out of this remains the same.
It is not particularly slippery for British scandals.
No noble titles seem to have been sold, no politician paid Parisian hotel bills, no extramarital toes sucked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has covered up donations to the British ruling Labour Party for more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) under the name of other people for four years, and that the party has failed to report this, something would have gotten along well without the contested Gordon Brown.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister had withdrawn from the call for an election, in a stupid way insulting the intelligence of the British by claiming that opinion polls did not influence this decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly perceptive leader of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once feared Brown from Stalin to Mr. Bean has developed.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a battered bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Badly thought-out proposals to amend tax laws have brought business associations against the government.
The loss of personal data by the tax authorities of 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative fraud.
A trio of retired generals started an uprising in the upper house in protest against cuts in military spending: to be a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the manifold donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's Secretary General (and its former Head of Fulfillment) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown is irrevocably heading for departure.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a turning point after which they feel it impossible to govern.
People neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their scepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that it is unlikely that a prime minister will improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there for long, this delay is over: the public service is beginning to leak; the cabinet ministers are beginning to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In one way, Brown's position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he wished to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant-in-chief.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction documents, for example, are linked to decisions made by Brown as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's mishap - like the long "money for nobility" investigation of political party financing - voters may assume it was him.
Still, Brown's situation isn't as bad as it looks
The crimes are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
Like Mr. Bean, no one died, or was completely cheated.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown's naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new urge to make political donations is a good example.
The garboeske of Abraham, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his goodwill.
It may be, but he was not entitled to make the decision.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's agreement, but not that it is illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's main financial collector, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far Brown has not been involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister's done half the work.
He has quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he watered down this determination by grasping for a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - to make the measure full, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, "the lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it's a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things that Mr Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the Independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with a thorough reform of political party funding.
This would require the hardliners of Labour to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly to give up the special financial relationship with the trade unions - bitter pills for a party comrade like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win voters back; and the only way he can achieve victory is through incontestable integrity and solid competence.
Card sharks
Is the credit crisis affecting America's credit card market?
If there's blood in the water, it's only natural that dorsal fins swirl around excitedly.
Now that America’s real estate market is ailing, predators are targeting the country’s credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of underfunded credit spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both derecognition and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are not recoverable or more than 30 days late.
Last month, HSBC announced that it had taken a $1.4 billion fee collection from its American consumer financing, partly due to the weakness of credit card holders.
It's still too early to panic.
Losses and defaults are still low.
According to Moody, the third-quarter default rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in US private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt case of bankruptcy applications, which in turn account for a large part of the credit card losses; the number of applications (and thus default fees) would increase again, whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
Industry also reports solid payment rates showing how much of its debt consumers pay off every month
and trust in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research company, expects that the 2007 output will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market: it is more likely that consumers take credit card debts, now that home loans dry out.
However, card issuers look at the flow of money rather than capital, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower’s creditworthiness.
They can even be of benefit to card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue to pay mortgage rates fall when real estate is less valuable than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among the redemption priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the stormier conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of the assets.
"We won't wake up one day and reassess the loans completely," says Gary Perlin, Capital One's Chief Financial Officer.
Even if a sudden undercover crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are much more real.
When lower house prices and credit reduction push America into recession, industry will undoubtedly face a more grim future.
Keep looking for these shark fins.
