Venus is the infernal twin of the earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to the Earth than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices on the Poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: The lightnings on Venus are shooting at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "primordial soup theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms in the ocean are said to have stimulated reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there was ever life there, it must have been in very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on earth, temperatures of 500 degrees Celsius sometimes prevail.
"Venus may be the devil's twin on Earth, but it's a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to the Earth in mass and size, has undergone such a completely different development, is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the beginning of the nineties no probe has been on its way specifically to explore this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighbouring planet with the Earth are greater than initially assumed," says the Esa.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents on the earthly winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second tiniest planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost as large with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, revolves around the sun in just under 225 days.
But it revolves much slower around itself: A Venus day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus hardly reminds the Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets were created under very similar conditions.
Both collected water that remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it accounts for most of the atmosphere on Venus.
