These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Those who combine the terms Sweden and Holzkiste think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wood crates manufactured in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue of works.
A large part of the ninety-four Brillo boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes of 1968, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now come to a sobering result: The six "Brillo Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably also the majority of the approximately one hundred other Brillo boxes of the "Type Stockholm", which are circulating on the international art market.
The prehistory is intertwined, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works in the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's consent - exhibited hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not (for reasons of cost) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo Carton Factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, but these were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at the time were rightly entered into the art and auction history as authorized original andy-warhol-brillo-boxes with the designation "Typ Stockholm".
Some of them have made more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at Moderna Museet, examined the six museum-owned Brillo Boxes as well as three privately owned Swedish houses, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their chipboard plates were first primed and sanded, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressed chipboard with a paint roll without primer - moreover, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to another conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious accusations" raised in the matter of soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, there has been a relentless silence.
